The bounding polynomial degree

may depend on the quantum numbers characterizing the process. 

This formulation of analyticity conditions might seem unnecessarily
complicated, especially, if one takes into account that the domain
()
is only a part of the full complex space of two variables describing
the process.
We use it because of two reasons. First, the results of the papers
,and
show that it leads to reasonable physical consequences. Second, even
in the case under consideration (binary processes) the corresponding
systems of bootstrap equations for the minimal parameters of the
extended theory turn out to be very complicated. In this case an
imprudent attempt to formulate more general requirements without
sufficient physical and mathematical motivation could lead to
inconsistency.

The examples that we analyze in the following sections illustrate the
structure and techniques of derivation of bootstrap equations.
However, before starting their consideration we would like to make a
short review of the Cauchy form method.



The Cauchy forms 
 

We are going to use the method (known from the complex analysis; see,
e.g.,
), which allows one to present the polynomialy bounded
meromorphic function of one complex variable as a uniformly converging
series of pole contributions (in what follows we call such
representations as the Cauchy forms or Cauchy expansions). The
possibility to work in the layer
 
(not only in the plane
)
is provided by the natural modification of the method
(see,):
all the coefficients are considered to be smooth (real-analytic)
functions of the parameter
.

