Numerical test of the convergence rapidity 
 

The numerical test of the convergence rapidity of
the series
() could be of great interest. This is because to check the
theoretical predictions of the dual models one often saturates the
quite similar to
()
identities (the so-called sum rules) with a
finite 
number of resonances.

Unfortunately the up-to-date information on the hadron spectrum is far
from being exhaustive (especially in the region
 GeV).
This means that only those sum rules that converge sufficiently
rapidly could undergo the experimental  verification. That is why it
would be extremely instructive to learn how to pick these identities
out of the infinite system of bootstrap and collapse conditions. In
this section, by way of treating the example of the string amplitude
discussed in the
Sec. ,
we suggest a possible approach to this problem in the realistic
situation.

